        <!-- Slide 3: Part A Introduction -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Part A: Communication Fundamentals</h1>
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h2>Why Communication Matters in Logistics</h2>
                <p>In the fast-paced world of supply chain and logistics, clear communication can mean the difference between:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>On-time delivery vs. delays</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Client satisfaction vs. complaints</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Team efficiency vs. confusion</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Career growth vs. stagnation</strong></li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p><strong>Remember:</strong> At Stride Logistics, we bridge gaps between traditional and modern systems. Your communication skills are the bridge between you and success.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 4: Eye Contact Mastery -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Eye Contact: The Foundation of Trust</h1>
            <h2>Why Eye Contact Matters</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Builds trust and credibility</strong> - Essential when discussing logistics solutions</li>
                <li><strong>Shows confidence and competence</strong> - Critical for client interactions</li>
                <li><strong>Demonstrates active engagement</strong> - Important in team meetings</li>
                <li><strong>Conveys sincerity</strong> - Vital for building professional relationships</li>
            </ul>
            
            <div class="dos-donts">
                <div class="dos">
                    <h3>✅ DO</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Maintain 60-70% eye contact during conversations</li>
                        <li>Look at the interviewer when answering questions</li>
                        <li>Make brief eye contact with all participants in group meetings</li>
                        <li>Use the "triangle technique" - eyes, nose, mouth</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="donts">
                    <h3>❌ DON'T</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Stare continuously (makes people uncomfortable)</li>
                        <li>Look at your phone or computer while speaking</li>
                        <li>Avoid eye contact completely (appears disinterested)</li>
                        <li>Look away when discussing important points</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 5: Body Language Fundamentals -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Body Language: Your Silent Communicator</h1>
            <h2>The 55-38-7 Rule</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <p><strong>55%</strong> Body language and visual cues</p>
                <p><strong>38%</strong> Tone of voice</p>
                <p><strong>7%</strong> Actual words spoken</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Professional Posture Guidelines</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Stand tall</strong> - Shoulders back, chin up</li>
                <li><strong>Sit forward</strong> - Shows engagement in meetings</li>
                <li><strong>Open gestures</strong> - Avoid crossed arms</li>
                <li><strong>Firm handshake</strong> - 2-3 seconds, web-to-web contact</li>
                <li><strong>Appropriate space</strong> - Maintain 3-4 feet in professional settings</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p><strong>Logistics Tip:</strong> When presenting shipping solutions or discussing freight challenges, confident body language reinforces your expertise.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 6: Active Listening -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Active Listening: The Key to Understanding</h1>
            <h2>Why Active Listening is Critical in Logistics</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Prevents costly misunderstandings in shipping instructions</li>
                <li>Builds stronger client relationships</li>
                <li>Helps identify hidden problems in supply chain processes</li>
                <li>Shows respect for colleagues and supervisors</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>The SOLER Technique</h3>
            <div class="star-method">
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>S - Square</h4>
                    <p>Face the speaker directly</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>O - Open</h4>
                    <p>Keep an open posture</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>L - Lean</h4>
                    <p>Lean in slightly to show interest</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>E - Eye</h4>
                    <p>Maintain appropriate eye contact</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
                <div class="star-item" style="display: inline-block;">
                    <h4>R - Relax</h4>
                    <p>Stay calm and focused</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 7: Small Talk Mastery -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Small Talk: Building Professional Bridges</h1>
            <h2>Why Small Talk Matters</h2>
            <p>Small talk is the foundation of professional relationships. It helps you:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Build rapport with clients before discussing logistics solutions</li>
                <li>Create comfortable environments for negotiations</li>
                <li>Establish trust in international business relationships</li>
                <li>Network effectively at industry events</li>
            </ul>
            
            <div class="dos-donts">
                <div class="dos">
                    <h3>✅ SAFE TOPICS</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Weather and current events</li>
                        <li>Professional interests and industry trends</li>
                        <li>Travel (especially relevant in logistics)</li>
                        <li>Local restaurants and culture</li>
                        <li>Recent achievements or projects</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="donts">
                    <h3>❌ AVOID</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Personal finances</li>
                        <li>Political opinions</li>
                        <li>Personal health issues</li>
                        <li>Negative gossip about colleagues</li>
                        <li>Controversial social topics</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 8: English Practice Importance -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>English Fluency: Your Global Advantage</h1>
            <h2>Why English Mastery is Essential</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <p><strong>Stride Logistics operates globally</strong> - English is the universal business language in logistics, connecting you with clients across continents.</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Daily Practice Strategies</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Think in English</strong> - Practice internal dialogue in English</li>
                <li><strong>Read logistics industry publications</strong> - Supply Chain Management Review, Logistics Management</li>
                <li><strong>Listen to business podcasts</strong> - Focus on logistics and supply chain content</li>
                <li><strong>Practice with colleagues</strong> - Use English in internal communications</li>
                <li><strong>Record yourself</strong> - Practice presentations and listen back</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Speak with confidence about freight forwarding, cargo tracking, and supply chain optimization in clear, professional English.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 9: Part B Introduction -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Part B: Professional Introductions</h1>
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h2>First Impressions in Logistics</h2>
                <p>You never get a second chance to make a first impression. In logistics, where trust and reliability are paramount, your introduction sets the tone for:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Client relationships worth millions in freight volume</li>
                    <li>Partnerships with shipping lines and carriers</li>
                    <li>Career advancement opportunities</li>
                    <li>International business negotiations</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 10: Interview Preparation -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Interview Excellence: Structure is Key</h1>
            <h2>The STAR Method for Behavioral Questions</h2>
            <div class="star-method">
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>S - Situation</h4>
                    <p>Set the context and background</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>T - Task</h4>
                    <p>Describe the challenge or responsibility</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>A - Action</h4>
                    <p>Explain what you did</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>R - Result</h4>
                    <p>Share the positive outcome</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h3>Example for Logistics Role:</h3>
                <p><strong>Situation:</strong> "Our client's shipment was delayed at port due to documentation issues..."</p>
                <p><strong>Task:</strong> "I needed to resolve this quickly to prevent further delays..."</p>
                <p><strong>Action:</strong> "I contacted the customs broker, coordinated with the shipping line..."</p>
                <p><strong>Result:</strong> "The shipment cleared within 24 hours, saving the client $50,000 in penalties."</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 11: Email and Meeting Etiquette -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Professional Communication Protocols</h1>
            <h2>Email Excellence</h2>
            <div class="dos-donts">
                <div class="dos">
                    <h3>✅ EMAIL BEST PRACTICES</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Clear, specific subject lines</li>
                        <li>Professional greeting and closing</li>
                        <li>Concise, structured content</li>
                        <li>Proofread before sending</li>
                        <li>Respond within 24 hours</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="donts">
                    <h3>❌ EMAIL MISTAKES</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>All caps (appears aggressive)</li>
                        <li>Too casual language</li>
                        <li>Reply all unnecessarily</li>
                        <li>Unclear requests or questions</li>
                        <li>Grammar and spelling errors</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Essential Corporate Phrases</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>"I wanted to follow up on..."</strong></li>
                <li><strong>"Please let me know if you need any clarification..."</strong></li>
                <li><strong>"I look forward to your response..."</strong></li>
                <li><strong>"Thank you for bringing this to my attention..."</strong></li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 12: Speaking with Confidence -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Confident Communication: Structure Your Success</h1>
            <h2>The PEP Formula for Clear Communication</h2>
            <div class="star-method" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);">
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>P - Point</h4>
                    <p>State your main message clearly</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>E - Evidence</h4>
                    <p>Provide supporting details</p>
                </div>
                <div class="star-item">
                    <h4>P - Point</h4>
                    <p>Restate your conclusion</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Building Structured Sentences</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Use transition words:</strong> "Furthermore," "However," "As a result"</li>
                <li><strong>Be specific:</strong> "reduced costs by 15%" instead of "saved money"</li>
                <li><strong>Use active voice:</strong> "I managed the project" not "The project was managed"</li>
                <li><strong>Pause for emphasis:</strong> Allow important points to sink in</li>
            </ul>
            
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <p><strong>Logistics Example:</strong> "Our new tracking system has improved delivery accuracy. Evidence shows we've reduced lost shipments by 25% and increased customer satisfaction scores by 30%. This tracking system is clearly delivering measurable value."</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 13: Handshake and Introduction Protocol -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>The Perfect Professional Introduction</h1>
            <h2>Handshake Mastery</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h3>The 3-Second Rule</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Web-to-web contact</strong> - Palm to palm, not fingertips</li>
                    <li><strong>2-3 firm pumps</strong> - Not too many, not too few</li>
                    <li><strong>Maintain eye contact</strong> - Shows confidence and respect</li>
                    <li><strong>Stand up if seated</strong> - Shows respect and professionalism</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Introduction Structure</h3>
            <div style="font-size: 1.3em; background: #f8f9fa; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px;">
                <p><strong>1. Greeting:</strong> "Good morning/afternoon"</p>
                <p><strong>2. Name:</strong> "I'm [First Name Last Name]"</p>
                <p><strong>3. Role:</strong> "I'm a [Position] at Stride Logistics"</p>
                <p><strong>4. Value:</strong> "I specialize in optimizing freight operations"</p>
                <p><strong>5. Engagement:</strong> "How can I help you today?"</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 14: Networking Fundamentals -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Networking: Building Your Professional Network</h1>
            <h2>Why Networking Matters in Logistics</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Logistics is relationship-driven - carriers, shippers, brokers</li>
                <li>Information sharing prevents supply chain disruptions</li>
                <li>Referrals drive 85% of logistics business</li>
                <li>Industry knowledge spreads through professional networks</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Networking Strategy</h3>
            <div class="dos-donts">
                <div class="dos">
                    <h3>✅ EFFECTIVE NETWORKING</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Ask about their logistics challenges</li>
                        <li>Share relevant industry insights</li>
                        <li>Exchange business cards professionally</li>
                        <li>Follow up within 48 hours</li>
                        <li>Offer help before asking for favors</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="donts">
                    <h3>❌ NETWORKING MISTAKES</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Talking only about yourself</li>
                        <li>Interrupting conversations</li>
                        <li>Being pushy or aggressive</li>
                        <li>Forgetting names immediately</li>
                        <li>Not following up</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 15: Articulating Achievements -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Articulating Your Value Proposition</h1>
            <h2>How to Talk About Your Achievements</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h3>The CAR Method</h3>
                <p><strong>C - Challenge:</strong> What problem did you face?</p>
                <p><strong>A - Action:</strong> What did you do about it?</p>
                <p><strong>R - Result:</strong> What was the positive outcome?</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Quantify Your Impact</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Instead of:</strong> "I improved delivery times"</li>
                <li><strong>Say:</strong> "I reduced average delivery times by 3 days, improving customer satisfaction by 40%"</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Logistics-Specific Achievement Examples</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>"Optimized routing algorithms, reducing fuel costs by 20%"</li>
                <li>"Implemented new inventory system, decreasing stockouts by 35%"</li>
                <li>"Negotiated with carriers, saving $500K annually in shipping costs"</li>
                <li>"Streamlined customs processes, reducing clearance time by 50%"</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 16: Corporate Culture Communication -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Corporate Culture: Getting Things Done</h1>
            <h2>Direct but Respectful Communication</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <p>In corporate logistics, time is money. Be clear, concise, and actionable while maintaining professionalism.</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Effective Corporate Phrases</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>"Let's align on next steps..."</strong></li>
                <li><strong>"I'll circle back with an update by..."</strong></li>
                <li><strong>"Can we deep dive into this issue?"</strong></li>
                <li><strong>"Let's touch base offline to discuss..."</strong></li>
                <li><strong>"I'll take point on this initiative..."</strong></li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Being Upfront and Solution-Oriented</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Identify problems early:</strong> "I've identified a potential delay..."</li>
                <li><strong>Present solutions:</strong> "Here are three options to resolve this..."</li>
                <li><strong>Take ownership:</strong> "I'll ensure this gets resolved by..."</li>
                <li><strong>Communicate progress:</strong> "Here's where we stand on the project..."</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 17: Professional Dos and Don'ts -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Professional Communication: Complete Guide</h1>
            <div class="dos-donts">
                <div class="dos">
                    <h3>✅ ALWAYS DO</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Arrive 5 minutes early</li>
                        <li>Dress one level above the dress code</li>
                        <li>Use professional email signatures</li>
                        <li>Send thank you notes after meetings</li>
                        <li>Ask clarifying questions</li>
                        <li>Keep confidential information secure</li>
                        <li>Speak clearly and at appropriate volume</li>
                        <li>Use people's names in conversation</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="donts">
                    <h3>❌ NEVER DO</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Interrupt others while speaking</li>
                        <li>Use slang in professional settings</li>
                        <li>Check phone during conversations</li>
                        <li>Gossip about colleagues or clients</li>
                        <li>Make promises you can't keep</li>
                        <li>Ignore cultural differences</li>
                        <li>Speak negatively about competitors</li>
                        <li>Forget to follow up on commitments</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 18: Part C - Activities Introduction -->
        <div class="slide activity-slide">
            <h1>Part C: Practice Makes Perfect</h1>
            <div class="highlight-box" style="background: white;">
                <h2>Time to Apply What You've Learned</h2>
                <p>The next 30 minutes will be spent in practical exercises. Remember:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Practice builds confidence</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Feedback accelerates improvement</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Repetition creates habits</strong></li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Activity Structure</h3>
            <ul style="font-size: 1.3em;">
                <li><strong>Activity 1:</strong> Professional introductions (8 minutes)</li>
                <li><strong>Activity 2:</strong> Elevator pitch practice (8 minutes)</li>
                <li><strong>Activity 3:</strong> Active listening exercises (8 minutes)</li>
                <li><strong>Debrief and Q&A:</strong> (6 minutes)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 19: Activity 1 - Professional Introductions -->
        <div class="slide activity-slide">
            <h1>Activity 1: Professional Introduction Practice</h1>
            <h2>Instructions (8 minutes total)</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box" style="background: white;">
                <h3>Breakout Room Exercise</h3>
                <p><strong>Time:</strong> 6 minutes practice + 2 minutes feedback</p>
                <p><strong>Setup:</strong> Groups of 3-4 people</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>What to Practice</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Professional handshake and introduction</li>
                <li>Eye contact maintenance</li>
                <li>Clear articulation of your role at Stride Logistics</li>
                <li>Engaging follow-up questions</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Scenarios to Practice</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Meeting a new client</strong> at a shipping conference</li>
                <li><strong>Introduction in a team meeting</strong> with new colleagues</li>
                <li><strong>Networking event</strong> with industry professionals</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p><strong>Focus Points:</strong> Confident posture, clear speech, professional demeanor</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 20: Activity 2 - Elevator Pitch -->
        <div class="slide activity-slide">
            <h1>Activity 2: Elevator Pitch Development</h1>
            <h2>Instructions (8 minutes total)</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box" style="background: white;">
                <h3>Individual Preparation + Partner Practice</h3>
                <p><strong>Time:</strong> 3 minutes preparation + 5 minutes practice</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>30-Second Elevator Pitch Structure</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Who you are:</strong> Name and role</li>
                <li><strong>What you do:</strong> Your expertise in logistics</li>
                <li><strong>Value proposition:</strong> How you help clients/company</li>
                <li><strong>Call to action:</strong> What you want from the listener</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Sample Framework</h3>
            <div style="background: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; font-style: italic;">
                "Hi, I'm [Name], a [Position] at Stride Logistics. I specialize in [Your expertise area - freight optimization/supply chain management/cargo tracking]. I help companies reduce shipping costs and improve delivery times through smart logistics solutions. I'd love to learn more about your supply chain challenges and see how we might collaborate."
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 21: Activity 3 - Active Listening -->
        <div class="slide activity-slide">
            <h1>Activity 3: Active Listening Practice</h1>
            <h2>Instructions (8 minutes total)</h2>
            <div class="highlight-box" style="background: white;">
                <h3>Partner Exercise</h3>
                <p><strong>Time:</strong> 4 minutes each direction</p>
                <p><strong>Setup:</strong> Pairs - Speaker and Listener roles</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Exercise Structure</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Round 1 (4 minutes):</strong> Person A describes a logistics challenge they've faced</li>
                <li><strong>Round 2 (4 minutes):</strong> Person B shares their experience</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Listener's Checklist</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>✅ Maintain eye contact</li>
                <li>✅ Use SOLER technique</li>
                <li>✅ Ask clarifying questions</li>
                <li>✅ Paraphrase what you heard</li>
                <li>✅ Avoid interrupting</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Sample Topics</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>A time when a shipment was delayed</li>
                <li>Dealing with difficult customers</li>
                <li>Learning new logistics software</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 22: Homework Assignment -->
        <div class="slide">
